<br>
Let's really take a look at that period, shall we?  <br>
1920's as the great supply side proving ground? Really?<br>
<br>
The Economy was in Depression from Jan. 1920-July 1921<br>
<br>
Sharp recession from May 1923-July 1924<br>
<br>
and mild recession from Oct. 1926-Nov. 1927 (<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.econlib.org/library/Enc/Recessions.html">1</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->)<br>
<br>
The much vaunted final tax cut did not happen until 1925, and was followed immediately by almost a year of recession.  The economy then grew again between november 1927 and August of 1929 (yes Virginia, the Great Depression was well under way before the market crash of Sept. 1929).  The depression lasted from Aug. 1929-Mar. 1933 (ibid).<br>
<br>
Hmmm yes, supply side theory is looking better and better eh?<br>
<br>
The point in my hypothetical concession on the 20s and the 60s, was that those periods were not relevant, not that I agreed with you. Turns out the data are not so good for the 20s either, eh? <p>Bumraz, EQ Shadowknight<br>
